This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG) as it proposes a technique for eXtreme Multi-label Learning (XML) that can easily scale to very large datasets containing millions of data points in very high-dimensional feature space. It also involves the use of a k-nearest neighbour classifier, which is a common machine learning technique. 

It could also belong to the sub-category of information retrieval (cs.IR) as the goal of XML is to automatically annotate a given data point with the most relevant subset of labels from an extremely large label set, which is a common task in information retrieval. 

The paper could also be relevant to computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL) as these fields often involve large-scale datasets and multi-label prediction tasks. 

Finally, it could also be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) as the proposed technique involves the use of machine learning to automatically annotate data points with relevant labels.
